{{Refimprove|date=September 2018}} {{Infobox football club | clubname = Afghan FC Chaman| image = AFCChaman.png | fullname = Afghan Football Club Chaman| nickname = | founded = {{Start date and age|1960}}| ground = Jamal Nasir Stadium, [[Chaman]]| capacity = 4,000| chairman = Haji Naseer Ali | mgrtitle = Head Coach | manager = Adam Khan | league = [[Pakistan Premier League]] | season = [[2014–15 Pakistan Premier League|2014–15]] | position = Pakistan Premier League, 10th | pattern_la1= _flareonwhite|pattern_b1=|pattern_ra1= _flareonwhite|leftarm1=E20E0E |body1=E20E0E |rightarm1=E20E0E |shorts1=E20E0E |socks1=E20E0E| |pattern_la2=_blueshoulders|pattern_b2=|pattern_ra2=_blueshoulders| leftarm2= FFFFFF|body2= FFFFFF|rightarm2= FFFFFF|shorts2=FFFFFF|socks2= CC0000 }}
'''Afghan Football Club Chaman''' or '''Afghan FC''' are a [[football (soccer)]] club playing in the [[Pakistan Premier League]] (PPL). The club is based in [[Chaman]] in [[Balochistan, Pakistan]], a border city near [[Afghanistan]]. The Afghan Club plays at their homeground Jamal Nasir Stadium in Chaman.
In 2000, Afghan FC Chaman played in an invitation tour at [[Kandahar Stadium]], Afghanistan, against a local team from [[Kandahar]]. During the third and final game of the tour, Taliban religious police burst into the ground and stopped the game in the middle. The Taliban arrested twelve of the Afghan FC Chaman players and had their heads shaved as punishment for wearing shorts.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2000/jul/18/rorymccarthy |publisher=''[[The Guardian]]'' |title=Taliban send off footballers in shorts |first=Rory |last=McCarthy |date=July 18, 2000 |access-date=January 3, 2018}}</ref>
Afghan FC Chaman are founding members of the Pakistan Premier League. Afghan FC avoided relegation in the 2006–07 season, finishing in 9th spot, 2 points above [[Wohaib F.C.]] who edged out [[HBL F.C.]] to survive as well.
{{Pakistan Premier League}}
