{{Infobox stadium | name = West Bromwich Road | nickname = | image = | caption = | fullname = | location = [[Walsall]], [[England]] | coordinates = {{Coord|52.5718|-1.9777|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | broke_ground = | built = | opened = | renovated = | expanded = | closed = | demolished = | owner = | surface = Grass | cost = | architect = | capacity = 4,000 | record_attendance = 4,000 | dimensions = | acreage = | tenants = [[Walsall F.C.]] }}
'''West Bromwich Road''' was a sports ground in [[Walsall]], [[England]]. It was the home ground of [[Walsall F.C.]] between 1893 and 1895, and again from 1900 until 1901.
==History== Following complaints from local residents, Walsall left [[the Chuckery]] ground at the end of the [[1892–93 Football League|1892–93 season]] to move to West Bromwich Road.,<ref>[http://www.footballgroundguide.com/old-grounds-and-stands/fellows_park_walsall.htm Fellows Park] Football Grounds Guide</ref> However, the ground was not ready for the start of the [[1893–94 Football League|1893–94 season]], and the first two matches were played at [[the Oval (Wednesbury)|the Oval]] in [[Wednesbury]]. West Bromwich Road featured a football pitch surrounded by a running track, with a stand on the western touchline and some banking behind the southern goal.<ref name=UD>Paul Smith & Shirley Smith (2005) ''The Ultimate Directory of English & Scottish Football League Grounds Second Edition 1888–2005'', Yore Publications, p144, {{ISBN|0954783042}}</ref>
The first League match played at West Bromwich Road was 5–1 win over [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]] on 23 September 1893, with 1,500 spectators present. Walsall left the ground at the end of the [[1894–95 Football League|1894–95 season]] to move to [[Fellows Park]], but returned midway through the [[1900–01 Football League|1900–01 season]] after being evicted from the new ground. After finishing the season at West Bromwich Road, the club returned to Fellows Park for the [[1901–02 Football League|1901–02 season]]. The final match at the ground was a 0–0 draw with [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] on 22 April 1901 with only 800 spectators in attendance. The site was later used for housing.<ref name=UD/>
